      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown, build, and braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Season the {{lamb-shanks}} all over with {{sea-salt-fine}} and {{black-pepper}}. Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over high heat and brown the shanks on all sides, 3 minutes per side. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{onion}}, {{carrot}}, {{garlic}}, {{rosemary}}, and {{bay-leaves}} around the shanks. Stir the {{tomato-puree}} into the {{red-wine}} and pour over, then add the {{stock-beef}}. The liquid should come about halfway up the shanks. Cook on low for 8 hours, until the meat pulls away from the bone easily. Transfer the shanks carefully. Strain the cooking juices into a saucepan and reduce over high heat for 10 minutes to a glossy sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Pour the braising liquid into a wide saucepan and boil hard for 10 minutes. The alcohol cooks off and the sauce concentrates to a glossy consistency",
              "cause": "Not reduced after the slow cooker stage",
              "symptom": "Sauce thin and wine-tasting after cooking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Continue cooking for another 1 to 2 hours. Lamb shank collagen needs time to break down, rushing it produces a tough result",
              "cause": "Slow cooker running below temperature, or very large shanks",
              "symptom": "Shanks still firm at 8 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Lift the shanks carefully with a slotted spoon and place them on a warm tray. They will hold together while you reduce the sauce",
              "cause": "Shanks cooked longer than 9 hours",
              "symptom": "Meat falling off the bone before serving"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lamb shanks are a restaurant dish at home prices. The slow cooker removes all technical skill from the equation, the only moment that requires attention is the browning, which takes ten minutes. Serve on mashed potato with the reduced sauce poured over and braised vegetables alongside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
